===Verb===
{{en-verb|past2=absorpt|past2_qual=archaic}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[include]] so that it no longer has [[separate]] existence; to [[overwhelm]]; to cause to [[disappear]] as if by [[swallowing]] up; to [[incorporate]]; to [[assimilate]]; to take in and [[use up]]. {{defdate|first attested c. 1350 to 1470.}}
#* '''1782''', {{w|William Cowper}}, ''On Observing some Names of Little Note''
#*: Dark oblivion soon '''absorbs''' them all.
#* {{RQ:Irving Sketch Book|title=Rural Life in England|page=124|passage=In some countries, the large cities '''absorb''' the wealth and fashion of the nation; they are the only fixed abodes of elegant and intelligent society, and the country is inhabited almost entirely by boorish peasantry.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To engulf, as in water; to [[swallow up]]. {{defdate|Attested from the late 15th century until the late 18th century.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1684-1690|author={{w|Thomas Burnet}}|title=The Sacred Theory of the Earth|passage=to be '''absorpt''', or swallowed up, in a lake of fire and brimstone.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[suck up]]; to [[drink in]]; to [[imbibe]], like a [[sponge]] or as the [[lacteals]] of the body; to chemically take in. {{defdate|first attested in the early 17th century.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|physics|chemistry}} To take in energy and convert it, as{{defdate|first attested in the early 18th century.}}
#: {{ux|en|Heat, light, and electricity are '''absorbed''' in the substances into which they pass.}}
## {{lb|en|transitive|physics}} in receiving a physical impact or vibration without recoil.
## {{lb|en|transitive|physics}} in receiving sound energy without repercussion or echo.
## {{lb|en|transitive|physics}} taking in [[radiant energy]] and converting it to a different form of energy, like heat.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[engross]] or [[engage]] wholly; to [[occupy]] fully. {{defdate|first attested in the late 18th century.}}
#* {{RQ:Burroughs Son of Tarzan|chapter=VIII|page=103|passage=Geeka was cooking dinner. As the little girl played she prattled continuously to her companion, propped in a sitting position with a couple of twigs. She was totally '''absorbed''' in the domestic duties of Geeka&nbsp;– so much so that she did not note the gentle swaying of the branches of the tree above her as they bent to the body of the creature that had entered them stealthily from the jungle.}}
#* '''1904''', {{w|Kazimierz Waliszewski}}, translated by Lady Mary Loyd, ''Ivan the Terrible'' Part 2 Chapter 3
#*: Livonian affairs held him tight, and were to '''absorb''' him for many a year.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To occupy or consume time. {{defdate|first attested in the mid 19th century.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} Assimilate mentally. {{defdate|first attested in the late 19th century.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|business}} To assume or pay for as part of a [[commercial]] [[transaction]].
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2006|author=Gunnar Almgren|passage=Among the most debatable is the contention that the profit margins of small employers are insufficient to '''absorb''' the costs of health insurance|title=Health Care Politics, Policy, and Services: A Social Justice Analysis}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[defray]] the costs.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To accept or purchase in quantity.

